"CORE_NARRATIVE: Current light field analysis relies on continuous spectral methods that fail under practical discrete sampling and inherently entangle illumination, depth, and material properties. By replacing spectral analysis with a physics-based three-layer angular decomposition and discrete geometric features, we fundamentally decouple these physical signals at the pixel level. This paradigm shift enables robust material identification and establishes a reliable theoretical foundation for depth estimation in complex non-Lambertian scenes.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open by contrasting the theoretical elegance of continuous spectral light field analysis (e.g., 2D-DFT) with its practical failure on discrete hardware (e.g., 9x9 microlens arrays), highlighting how this hardware-software mismatch inherently entangles illumination, depth, and material signals.\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Transition by demonstrating that existing attempts to handle non-Lambertian surfaces merely mask the symptoms of entangled signals rather than solving the root cause: the inability to physically decouple material residuals from depth and illumination under strict discrete angular constraints.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: Justify the three-layer decomposition and dual-mask routing as direct mathematical and architectural responses to the discrete sampling limitation, explicitly showing how extracting geometric angular gradients from the residual layer bypasses the continuous resolution requirement of spectral methods.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Structure the experiments to first prove the decoupling efficacy via the Random Forest classifier's high accuracy (89.6%) and large effect size (Cohen's d = 0.983) on geometric features, then demonstrate the downstream benefit through the dual-mask network's improved performance in mixed Lambertian/non-Lambertian scenes.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Conclude by reiterating that shifting from continuous spectral assumptions to discrete geometric physics fundamentally resolves the signal entanglement bottleneck, establishing a new theoretical baseline for practical light field depth estimation and material analysis."